I",<p>How do I reapply a commit, so I actually want the commit run twice? Say I do something cool, then do something uncool, and want to do that cool thing again, without having to mess around with history?</p>

<p>Say I pull in some dependency which adds a readme file somewhere, then I delete the readme file, then I update the dependency which pulls in the file again.</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>we use Gitâ€™s cherry-pick command, which applies it as a patch and immediately commits it with the same commit message):</p>
</blockquote>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>git cherry-pick 89bec60
</code></pre></div></div>

